<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-355-606  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 355 606.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  April 5 1990 n1208 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lend detailed plans a helping hand. (project management systemscan not substitute for good management and planning)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Powell, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A project management system can be used to develop a plan andprovide monitoring of the project against the plan, but goodmanagement skills and detailed planning are as important.andP;  Projectmanagement software packages are available for all levels ofproject complexity, but not all types of projects can benefit fromsuch systems.andP;  A viable project management system should includethe ability to record all the tasks which make up a project, anincremental update capability to account for new task data orsub-project spin-offs, an itemization of all personnel and otherresources required, the ability to show where and what resourcesare needed, and a diary or or calendar system that tracks thestages of the project and the related resources.andP;  Example projectmanagement packages include Microsoft Project, Hoskyns PMW andPertmaster.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Project Management SystemsUtilizationApplicationsFunctionsRequirements Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>